A second round of hierarchical clustering was then applied to this matrix, identifying stable groupings that consistently emerged across runs. These stable clusters — referred to in this article as meta-clusters — reflect recurrent textual affinities independent of run-to-run variation. Their distribution is visualized in a co-occurrence heatmap (
                        Figure 2
                     ), which highlights the strength of associations between texts across the 100 iterations.

A second clustering solution was then derived by applying Ward’s hierarchical clustering directly to the averaged distance matrix. Unlike the meta-clusters, which reflect co-clustering frequency, this second approach sorts texts based on cumulative pairwise dissimilarity. The result is a dendrogram showing hierarchical relationships among all texts, with cluster boundaries generated by an automated distance threshold (
                        Figure 3
                     ).
